<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="382" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,788,2037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1111,1136]" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Pérez &amp; Rodríguez &amp; Asenjo, 2018" authorityName="Pérez &amp; Rodríguez &amp; Asenjo" authorityYear="2018" box="[328,441,1111,1136]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shapra" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[328,441,1111,1136]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">H. shapra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[447,537,1111,1136]" pageId="6" pageNumber="382" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[447,530,1111,1136]" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is easily differentiated from other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Solier" authorityYear="1849" box="[1044,1212,1111,1136]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="382" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1044,1212,1111,1136]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Homalotrichus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the combination of the following characters: head width about 8× eye width (
<figureCitation box="[832,948,1148,1173]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Fig. 6A,C</figureCitation>
), pronotum convex, lateral margin strongly convex and narrowing to base and pronotal impressions oval-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[937,1054,1183,1208]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Fig. 6A,C</figureCitation>
). The male is easily differentiated from males of other species by not having a marked sexual dimorphism: absence of triangular process on tergum VII (
<figureCitation box="[205,326,1255,1280]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Fig. 6A–B</figureCitation>
) and the absence of a huge curved horn on tergite VIII.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="385" pageId="6" pageNumber="382" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,788,2037]" box="[199,772,1292,1317]" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1292,1317]" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[351,455,1292,1317]" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Holotype</typeStatus>
male (BL: 3.80; BW: 1.08).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,788,2037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">
Head, antennae, pronotum, and abdomen black, elytra dark brown. Mouthparts light brown, labial palps, maxillary palps dark brown. Coxae and trochanter dark brown. First to fifth tarsomeres brown (
<figureCitation box="[1220,1355,1364,1389]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Figs. 6A–B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,788,2037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">
Head hexagonal, wider than long (HW: 0.67; HL: 0.46) with anterior margin straight, head width about 8× eye width. Neck narrower than head (NW: 0.49). Cephalic disk (
<figureCitation box="[950,1051,1436,1461]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
) with micro-punctation spread heterogeneously forming smooth areas. One macroseta near anterior edge of eye, one macroseta near posterior edge of eye and one macroseta near posterior margin of head (
<figureCitation box="[843,931,1508,1533]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Fig. 6C</figureCitation>
). Eyes large and prominent, longer than wide (YL: 0.184; YW: 0.08) located laterally in middle part. Antennae longer than length of head and pronotum together, antennomere 1 the longest, slightly incrassate apically, 2–3 elongate and strongly incrassate apically, 4 slightly longer than wide, antennomere 5 subquadrate, from 5 on broader than 2–4 and with distinct basal ridge, antennomere 10 wider than length (width:length = 0.14:0.13), terminal antennomere about 1.4× longer than wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,788,2037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">
Pronotum convex (
<figureCitation box="[419,554,1687,1712]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Figs. 6A–C</figureCitation>
) wider than long (PW: 0.85; PL: 0.64), margin anterior slightly convex and posterior margin straight, lateral margin irregular, strongly convex and narrowing to base. Pronotal disc with setigerous punctures spread irregularly. Two pronotal impressions oval-shaped near posterior margin. Three macrosetae near each lateral margin and two setae near each posterior corner. Two pairs of macroseta near anterior margin. Two macrosetae near posterior margin. Scutellum subtriangular with rounded apex and with micropunctation (
<figureCitation box="[284,412,1868,1893]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Figs. 6A,C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,788,2037]" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[283,416,1903,1928]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="382">Figs. 6A–C</figureCitation>
) longer than wide (EL: 1.15; EW: 1.11) with apex wider than base. Elytron with five well defined lines of punctures and scattered punctures near outer lateral margin. First longitudinal line with five setae near inner lateral margin, line of seven setae near outer lateral margin, line of six setae very close outer lateral margin.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="383" startId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" targetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1831,2007]" pageId="7" pageNumber="383">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,1831,1853]" pageId="7" pageNumber="383">FIGURE 6.</emphasis>
(A–J) (A–H) 
<taxonomicName authority="Pérez &amp; Rodríguez &amp; Asenjo, 2018" authorityName="Pérez &amp; Rodríguez &amp; Asenjo" authorityYear="2018" box="[423,653,1831,1853]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="383" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shapra" status="sp. nov.">
