<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="8" pageNumber="384">Legs. Procoxae conical narrowly separated by prosternal process. Mesocoxae contiguous, elongated and oblique, separated by mesosternal process. Metacoxae transversal, with conical region that articulates with trochanter. Protrochanter triangular, mesotrochanter triangular, and metatrochanter triangular. Profemora, mesofemora and metafemora long, mesofemora tapering slightly towards its extreme. Left protibiae with a defined row of four spines and two setae in external-lateral margin, right protibiae with well defined row of five spines and two setae in external-lateral margin, mesotibiae and metatibiae with spines. Tarsi 5-segmented, tarsomere 1–4 small, as long as wide (0.03:0.04). Tarsomere 5 longer than wide (0.20; 0.04).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="8" pageNumber="384">
Abdomen margined (
<figureCitation box="[451,548,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="384">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
). Terga III-VII (morphological segments) with subbasal carinae complete. Segments III-VI with two laterosternites per segment, segment VII with only one laterosternite per segment. Tergum VII without a triangular process that is more or less lamellar at midline, near posterior margin. Tergum VIII emarginate, trapezoidal with 16 macrosetae, 6 arranged near each lateral margin and 4 macrosetae in middle forming a rectangle (
<figureCitation box="[387,478,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="384">Fig. 6D</figureCitation>
). Sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[657,741,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="384">Fig. 6E</figureCitation>
) with membranous lobe on posterior margin, 6 macrosetae in each lateral-posterior third. Tergum IX visible in ventral view, many setae in distal part (dorsal view). Sternite IX an elongate plate.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,896,2010,2032]" pageId="8" pageNumber="384">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,896,2010,2032]" box="[151,896,2010,2032]" pageId="8" pageNumber="384">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,2010,2032]" pageId="8" pageNumber="384">FIGURE 7.</emphasis>
Distribution map of new Peruvian species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Solier" authorityYear="1849" box="[739,891,2010,2032]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="384" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[739,891,2010,2032]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="384">Homalotrichus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">
Aedeagus symmetrical, with median lobe bulbous at base, narrow in middle part. Parameres thin, curved, not exceed length of aedeagus. In ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[649,735,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Fig. 6F</figureCitation>
), parameres fused basally. In lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[1218,1300,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Fig.6G</figureCitation>
), parameres with acute projection near base. In dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[713,806,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Fig. 6H</figureCitation>
), base of median lobe with an oval membranous area. Internal sclerites as in 
<figureCitation box="[403,532,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Figs. 6F–H</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis box="[199,283,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Female</emphasis>
similar to male, except sternite IX (
<figureCitation box="[685,764,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Fig. 6J</figureCitation>
) divided perpendicularly and forming two plates with many setae in distal part and absence of acute projection in tergum IX (
<figureCitation box="[880,957,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1831,1853]" captionTargetBox="[158,1426,218,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,218,1770]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. (A–J) (A–H) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., holotype male: (A) habitus, dorsal view; (B) habitus, lateral view; (C) arrangement of setae on head, pronotum and elytra; (D) male tergum VIII (T8); (E) male sternite VIII (S8); (F), aedeagus, ventral view; (G) aedeagus, lateral view; (H) aedeagus, dorsal view. (I–J) Homalotrichus shapra sp. nov., paratype female from Cajamarca, Cerro Negro: (I) female tergum IX (T9) and tergum X (T10), dorsal view; (J) female tergum IX (T9) and sternite IX (S9), ventral view. Dotted areas (E–J) represent membranous areas. Circles in (D) represent the external opening of spiracles. Arrows in (I) indicate the external opening of abdominal glands." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1458532/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">
Fig. 
<date box="[933,957,332,357]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">6I</date>
</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,573]" box="[199,423,367,392]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,367,392]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Habitat.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="385" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,404,429]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known from Chugurmayo and Cerro Negro localities, 
<collectingRegion box="[993,1116,404,429]" country="Peru" name="Cajamarca" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Cajamarca</collectingRegion>
, northern region of 
<collectingCountry box="[1348,1402,405,428]" name="Peru" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Peru</collectingCountry>
, at 
<quantity box="[151,236,439,464]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.626" pageId="9" pageNumber="385" unit="m" value="3626.0">3626 m</quantity>
and 
<quantity box="[290,375,439,464]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.656" pageId="9" pageNumber="385" unit="m" value="3656.0">3656 m</quantity>
respectively (
<figureCitation box="[533,601,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="8.[151,250,2010,2032]" captionText="FIGURE 7. Distribution map of new Peruvian species of Homalotrichus." pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="385" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,476,501]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pérez &amp; Rodríguez &amp; Asenjo" authorityYear="2018" box="[578,655,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Homalotrichus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="385" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shapra">shapra</taxonomicName>
” means hair in Quechua. It refers to the large number of setae on sternite VIII. This is a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1177,548,573]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,151,573]" box="[199,1177,548,573]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,548,573]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">Remarks.</emphasis>
The number of spines on the protibiae varies between 
<quantity box="[929,1014,548,573]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.143" metricValueMax="1.27" metricValueMin="1.016" pageId="9" pageNumber="385" unit="in" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4 – 5 in</quantity>
the 
<typeStatus box="[1062,1173,549,573]" pageId="9" pageNumber="385">paratypes</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
